===Etymology 2===
Origin uncertain, either
* from a northern English dialectal term {{m|en|lake}}/{{m|en|laik||to play}} (around 1300, from {{etyl|non|en}} {{m|non|leika||to play (as opposed to work)}}), with an intrusive ''-r-'' as is common in southern British dialects; or
* a shortening of {{m|en|skylark}} (1809), sailors' slang, "play roughly in the rigging of a ship", because the common European larks were proverbial for high-flying; Dutch has a similar idea in {{m|nl|speelvogel||playbird, a person of markedly playful nature}}.

